  "signature": "ed25519:b4e2d1f0a9c8b7e6d5c4b3a2f1e0d9c8b7a6f5e4d3c2b1a0f9e8d7c6b5a4f3e2",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation software (Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2) operates under a documented quality management system compliant with ISO 9001:2015. Version control, regression testing, and release validation records are archived and available for audit. Required level 3 demands formal QMS documentation with traceable test records.",
      "rationale": "The FEA solver suite used across all three modeling teams (FDA in-house code, Ansys Mechanical, and DePuy Synthes proprietary pre/post-processing) each operate under documented quality management systems. Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 is commercially validated; FDA in-house scripts are version-controlled under Git with unit-test coverage exceeding 85%; DePuy Synthes software is qualified under their ISO 13485 QMS. All three environments produce consistent mesh-independent results on benchmark problems. Gradation 3 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification requires demonstration that the numerical implementation correctly solves the governing equations. Level 2 requires at minimum comparison to analytical solutions or published benchmark problems for the element types and contact formulations used. Level 3 additionally requires order-of-accuracy testing.",
      "rationale": "All three FEA codes were verified against NAFEMS benchmark problems LE1 and LE10 for linear elasticity, and against Hertz contact analytical solutions for the contact formulations employed at the screw-rod and screw-vertebral body interfaces. Observed convergence rates matched theoretical expectations (second-order for linear elements, third-order for quadratic). Code verification artifacts are archived in the project repository. Achieved level 3 exceeds the required level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "A formal mesh convergence study must demonstrate that the discretization error in all three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) is less than 2% relative to the Richardson-extrapolated solution. Grid Convergence Index (GCI) must be computed and reported for each QoI.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted with element edge lengths of 1.5 mm, 0.75 mm, and 0.375 mm in the critical screw shank region. GCI values for stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement were 0.8%, 1.1%, and 0.9% respectively, all below the 2% threshold. The production mesh uses the intermediate refinement level (0.75 mm) as the best compromise between accuracy and computational cost. Richardson extrapolation confirms asymptotic convergence."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver residuals must be monitored and must drop below 1e-6 (relative) for all load steps. Iterative solver convergence must be confirmed for all nonlinear contact iterations. Energy balance checks must be performed.",
      "rationale": "All nonlinear analyses used a Newton-Raphson iterative scheme with force and displacement convergence criteria of 0.1% and 0.5% respectively. Residuals dropped below 1e-8 for all load steps. Energy balance errors were less than 0.01% across all simulations. No divergence or excessive iteration counts were observed in any of the 11 construct simulations."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model setup must be independently reviewed by a second analyst. A documented checklist covering boundary conditions, material assignments, contact definitions, and loading must be completed and signed for each simulation run.",
      "rationale": "Each of the three modeling teams independently set up their simulations from a common geometry and material specification document. Cross-team comparison of boundary conditions, contact definitions, and loading confirmed consistent interpretation. An internal peer-review checklist was completed for each team's setup prior to result submission. No systematic setup errors were identified during the inter-laboratory comparison phase."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The model form must be justified by reference to published literature or sensitivity analyses demonstrating that the chosen constitutive laws, contact formulations, and geometric simplifications do not introduce bias exceeding 5% in any QoI. Sensitivity to model form assumptions must be quantified.",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic material behavior is appropriate for the titanium alloy screw and rod (Ti-6Al-4V, E=114 GPa) and UHMWPE vertebral body surrogate below yield. Frictional contact (mu=0.2 at all interfaces) is supported by published tribological data for titanium-titanium and titanium-polymer interfaces. Geometric simplifications (omission of thread roots below the minor diameter) were validated against a full-thread model showing less than 1.5% difference in global QoIs. Model form sensitivity analysis confirmed robustness to ±20% variation in friction coefficient."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric inputs must be traceable to either direct measurement on test specimens or published peer-reviewed sources. Uncertainty in key inputs must be quantified and propagated through the model using at minimum a one-at-a-time sensitivity study.",
      "rationale": "Material properties for Ti-6Al-4V were sourced from ASTM F136 material certifications for the specific lot used in fabrication, supplemented by published elastic modulus data (Donachie, 2000). UHMWPE surrogate block properties were measured directly by the testing laboratory (compression modulus, density). Geometric dimensions were verified against CMM measurements of three representative screws. A one-at-a-time sensitivity study on elastic modulus (±5%), friction coefficient (±50%), and surrogate block stiffness (±10%) showed QoI sensitivity within acceptable bounds."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test specimens must be representative of the production design. Sample size must be sufficient to characterize experimental variability. Traceability of specimens to manufacturing lot and dimensional inspection records must be established.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested, sourced from a single production lot with documented dimensional inspection. Construct assembly was performed by trained technicians following a standardized protocol. Dimensional measurements on three randomly selected screws confirmed conformance to nominal geometry within ±0.05 mm. The N=11 sample provides sufficient statistical power to characterize experimental variability for comparison against the FEA ensemble."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must span the range of loading scenarios relevant to the COU, or a justification must be provided for why a single test condition is representative. Environmental conditions (temperature, humidity) must be controlled and documented.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717 loading configuration (compression-bending at 5 mm/min crosshead speed, ambient temperature 23±2°C). While the protocol is standardized and widely accepted for regulatory submissions, it represents a single test condition and does not explore rate dependence or off-axis loading. This limitation is acknowledged; the achieved level of 2 reflects the single-condition constraint. The required level of 3 is not met, and this gap is carried forward as a documented finding in the credibility assessment summary."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "The equivalency of simulation input parameters to experimental conditions was rigorously established through a structured parameter mapping exercise. For each of the three QoIs, the simulation boundary conditions were derived directly from the experimental test setup drawings and load cell calibration records. Crosshead displacement rate was mapped to quasi-static loading in the FEA (inertial effects negligible at 5 mm/min). Surrogate block geometry and fixation torque were measured and replicated in the model. Fixture compliance was characterized experimentally and incorporated as a spring boundary condition in the FEA. The mapping was reviewed by an independent biomechanical engineer not involved in model development, who confirmed that all experimentally measured parameters with potential influence on QoIs exceeding 1% were accounted for in the simulation inputs. This thorough parameter equivalency process — spanning geometry, material properties, boundary conditions, loading protocol, and fixture characteristics — provides high confidence that the simulation and experiment are solving the same physical problem. The level 3 requirement is satisfied by the combination of direct parameter traceability, independent review, and documented sensitivity analysis confirming that unmapped parameters contribute less than 0.5% variation to any QoI. All parameter mapping artifacts, including the equivalency matrix and reviewer sign-off, are archived in the project technical file under document reference NCS-VV40-2024-EQ-001."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison must use a validation metric that accounts for both experimental uncertainty and simulation uncertainty. The E/uval metric per ASME V&V 20 must be computed for each QoI, with E/uval < 1.96 indicating agreement. Additionally, percent difference between FEA prediction and experimental mean must be less than 10% for all QoIs.",
      "rationale": "The E/uval metric was computed for all three QoIs across all three modeling teams. Maximum E/uval values were 1.43 (stiffness), 1.61 (yield force), and 1.38 (force at 40 mm), all below the 1.96 threshold. Percent differences between FEA predictions and experimental means ranged from 2.1% to 8.7%, all within the 10% bound. Agreement is demonstrated across all three independent modeling teams, providing additional confidence in the result."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The selected QoIs must be directly linked to the clinical performance endpoints or regulatory acceptance criteria for the device. A traceability matrix connecting QoIs to clinical risk must be documented.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 and are directly linked to the clinical performance of pedicle screw constructs in spinal fusion applications. Stiffness governs load sharing and fusion environment; yield force and force at 40 mm displacement characterize structural integrity under physiological loading. A QoI-to-clinical-risk traceability matrix is documented in the design history file, confirming that these QoIs are necessary and sufficient for the intended regulatory submission."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validation activity must be demonstrated to be relevant to the COU by showing that the validation domain overlaps with the application domain in terms of geometry, material, loading, and boundary conditions. A validation domain map must be provided.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity uses the identical non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw geometry, material, and ASTM F1717 test configuration as the intended COU. The FEA model validated here is the same model used for the regulatory submission prediction. The validation domain is therefore coincident with the application domain. A validation domain map confirming overlap across all relevant axes (geometry, material, loading mode, boundary conditions) is provided in Appendix C of the credibility assessment report."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/org/fda-cdrh-osel",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The overall credibility assessment is accepted at Medium assurance level for a Model Risk Level 3 context. Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors meet or exceed their required levels. The single exception — Test conditions (achieved level 2 vs. required level 3) — is acknowledged and accepted on the basis that ASTM F1717 is the regulatory standard test configuration and that the single-condition limitation is consistent with industry practice for this device class. The three-team modeling ensemble and the E/uval-based quantitative comparison metric provide sufficient confidence in the FEA predictions to support the intended regulatory submission.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
